1. On your Windows Server VM, create a new folder named 'MusicShare' on the D: drive and share it with the network using the Share Wizard.
=>Open File Explorer on the server.
Go to D: drive 
Right-click in an empty area → New → Folder → Name it MusicShare.
Right-click the MusicShare folder → Properties → Sharing tab → Advanced Sharing.
Check Share this folder.
Click Permissions:
Remove Everyone if present.
Add the MusicLovers group (from step 3 below) and grant Full Control (or Change) at share level for now.
Click OK to finish sharing. The share path will be \\YourServerName\MusicShare.

2. Set NTFS permissions on the 'MusicShare' folder so that the user 'Student1' has Read & Write access, while 'Student2' has Read-only access.
=>Right-click MusicShare folder → Properties → Security tab → Edit.
Click Add and select your test users:
Add Student1 (or equivalent) → Grant Modify (which includes Read & Write).
Add Student2 (or equivalent) → Grant Read & execute (Read-only).
Remove unnecessary groups (e.g., Users or Everyone) if they have broad access.
Click Apply → OK. (Inheritance may need to be disabled if you want strict control.)

3. Configure Share permissions for 'MusicShare' so that only members of the 'MusicLovers' group can access the share, and all others are denied.
=>Right-click MusicShare → Properties → Sharing tab → Advanced Sharing → Permissions.
Remove Everyone.
Click Add → Select the MusicLovers group.
Grant Change or Full Control to MusicLovers.
Ensure no other groups/users have access (this denies everyone else at the share level).
Click OK → Apply.

4. Simulate these access scenarios: log in as 'Student1' and try to copy a file into 'MusicShare', then log in as 'Student2' and attempt to delete a file from the same folder. Write down what happens in each case and explain why based on the permissions set.\
=>Scenario A: Log in as 'Student1' (member of MusicLovers)

Map the network drive: \\YourServerName\MusicShare or browse to it.
Copy a test file (e.g., create a text file on desktop and copy it) into the folder.
Expected Result: Succeeds (Read + Write works).
Explanation: Student1 has Modify NTFS permissions (allows write/create) + sufficient Share permissions via the MusicLovers group. Effective access = Write allowed.

Scenario B: Log in as 'Student2' (member of MusicLovers)

Browse to the share.
Attempt to delete a file that was copied earlier.
Expected Result: Fails with "Access Denied" error.
Explanation: Student2 has only Read NTFS permissions (no delete/write) even though they can access the share via MusicLovers group. Share permissions allow entry, but NTFS is more restrictive and blocks modification/deletion.
